 APPENDED 2026-07-24 — task-20260724-c014 (delivery layer: paste -> submit)
================================================================================
 Why: the 2026-07-20 "paste-sans-submit" stall recurred on Claude Code v2.1.218
 (Jesse Thaler review issue #6, part 3). The seal above was green because the
 spec's Init started a worker at pc = "sending" — it ASSUMED the briefing had
 been submitted, so the reachable bad state "pasted-but-not-submitted -> idle
 forever" was not in the state space at all. An abstraction gap, not a proof.

 The spec now models the handshake one floor lower: a worker starts at
 pc = "delivering" with delivery = "pasted", against an ADVERSARIAL TUI whose
 readiness is UNFAIR (may stay FALSE for unboundedly many ticks). Weak fairness
 sits on the Delivery group — the confirm loop keeps trying — never on the
 environment. So no fixed retry window can be sufficient, by construction.

 New safety  : NoSilentAbandon, NoWorkBeforeSubmit, InteractiveSkipsDelivery
 New liveness: BriefingResolves ==
                 (delivery = "pasted") ~> (delivery \in {"submitted","escalated"})

 Three runs are recorded.
   RUN 3 (shipped cfg, BoundedNudgeBudget = FALSE) — must PASS.
   RUN 4 (adversarial, BoundedNudgeBudget = TRUE)  — must FAIL on
         NoSilentAbandon, proving the delivery layer is not vacuous. Its
         4-state counterexample IS the field trace: paste, two swallowed
         submits, budget spent, silent give-up, pc = "delivering" forever.
   RUN 5 (adversarial, INVARIANTS reduced to TypeOK so TLC gets past the
         safety violation and reaches the temporal check) — must FAIL on
         BriefingResolves (and NoLivelock). Reproduce that cfg with:
           python3 -c "import re; s=open('cs_pilot_interactive_fsm_bounded_nudge.cfg').read(); \
             open('/tmp/c014_liveness.cfg','w').write( \
             re.sub(r'INVARIANTS\n(?:    \w+\n)+\n','INVARIANTS\n    TypeOK\n\n',s))"

 Verdict: RUN 3 passed; RUNs 4 and 5 produced the expected counterexamples.
 The pre-fix bounded-window-then-silent-return design is now mechanically
 refuted; only confirm-or-escalate model-checks clean.

